Introduction

In this project, we are going to take a closer look at the used car market. I always wondered how some cars could see their value rising so quickly while having more than 30/40 years. I remember having a lot of discussions with my father on which car would be the next rising star of the classic car market. Therefore, I’m going to study the evolution of prices in this market and try to understand which factors influence the market.

Our project is going to be based on the 3 different datasets:

—1st Dataset: true_car_listings is a data frame gathering 1.2 million used cars on the US market thanks to the website TrueCar. This dataset will allow us to compare different models, see how the different versions of a car, the mileage, and the year influence the price.

—2nd Dataset: hist_cars is a data frame recording the market value of 4 different cars since 2006. These 4 cars are collection cars that have different market trajectories: 1986 Audi GT, 1986 Renault R5 Turbo 1, 1987 Ferrari 328 GTS, and 1977 Porsche 911 Carrera Turbo. These data have been found on the website Hagerty.

—3rd Dataset: autos is a data frame gathering several characteristics of used cars. This data will allow us to class car according to their gearbox, power(Hp), mileage, year, category, and damage suffered.

Thanks to this Datasets, I’m going to try to answer to different questions:

  • Which are the cars that are more likely to see their value increases in the future?

  • When is the best time to buy used cars cost-efficiently speaking ?

  • Which factors influence the used car market price ?

Which are the cars that are more likely to see their value increases in the future?

Using the dataset hist_cars, we are going to study the behavior of 4 differents cars that are the 1986 Audi GT, 1986 Renault R5 Turbo 1, 1987 Ferrari 328 GTS, and 1977 Porsche 911 Carrera Turbo in order to try to highlight any comon points between these 4 vehicles. Here is the market evolution since their production year :

From this graph we can see that the prices have not decreased a lot between their production year and 2006. However we can notice different trajectories starting from there. For the 1977 Porsche 911 Carrera Turbo, there is a huge increase of the price between 2006 and 2015 of more than 800% while decreasing from 2015 to 2018. The 1986 Audi GT, conversely, saw its price staying flat for more than 20 years.

Now that we have a clear idea of the evolution of the price of these models, let’s see their behavior in the future.

For the 1977 Porsche 911 Carrera Turbo:

Thanks to the function ‘lm’ we are able to get the linear model of the price’s evolution. This function will allow us to predict the future trends of these cars’ markets. This approximation should be able to lead us to a more concrete understanding of which car’s value increases and why.

Here is the graph showing how should the price of each car behave in the next 20 years, using the formula :

\[ YearCoefficient * year - InterceptCoefficient \]

new_year= c(2018:2038)
data1 <- data.frame(
  new_year,
  Price_predict = 3897*new_year-7735823
  )

ggplot(data1,aes(x=data1$new_year,y=data1$Price_predict)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_line()+
  labs(x="Year",y="Price Prediction (in $)", title = "Price projection for the 1977 Porsche 911 Carrera Turbo from 2018 to 2038")

According to these estimations, the best investisment would we the 1986 Renault R5 Turbo 1. This car’s value will see an increase of approximately 170% in the next 20 years. This is due mainly to its scarcity and to the palmares of the car. This car has competed in the WRC(World Rallye Championship) and won many titles which makes it a colletor car for many lovers of this sport. Moreover, this extreme sportcar has only been produced 1690 times conversely to the 1986 Audi GT more than 40000 times.

When is the best time to buy used cars cost-efficiently speaking ?

In order to determine the cost efficiency, we first need to take into account the mileage value which is a determinant factor in the price of the cars. We know that when the mileage of a car increases the price decreases. In order to avoid this parameter, we are only going to take into account the cars with a mileage less than 30000 miles in order to consider the cars of the dataset in a well-preserved state.

ggplot(g1,aes(x=Year,y=mean_year))+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  labs(x="Year",y="Mean Price(in $)", title = "Mean price of cars per Year of production")

Year with the best compromise cost-efficiency speaking : Year : 2000

We can conclude from this result that the best time to buy a car is 18 years after its production.

Which factors influence the used car market price ?

Here is our 3rd dataset autos.csv that gathers cars prices along with their caracteristics which will help us understand which of those are influencing the price.

exp_data2 <- data2 %>% 
  select(price,vehicleType,yearOfRegistration,gearbox,powerPS,brand,model,notRepairedDamage,kilometer) %>%
  filter(price >= 500 & price <= 1000000) %>%
  filter(powerPS >= 50 & powerPS <= 1500) %>% 
  filter(notRepairedDamage == "ja" | notRepairedDamage == "nein") %>%
  filter(gearbox == "manuell" | gearbox== "automatik") %>%
  filter(vehicleType == "cabrio"|vehicleType == "coupe"|vehicleType == "limousine"|vehicleType== "suv")

names(exp_data2) <- c("Price", "VehiculeCategory", "YearOfRegistration", "Gearbox", "Hp", "Make", "Model", "Damage", "Mileage")
levels(exp_data2$VehiculeCategory) <- c("NA", "andere","bus", "Convertible", "Coupe", "kleinwagen", "Kombi","Sedan","SUV")
levels(exp_data2$Gearbox) <- c("NA", "Automatic", "Manual")
levels(exp_data2$Damage) <- c("NA", "Yes", "No")

exp_data2$PriceRange <- NA
if (exp_data2$Price  <= 10000) {
  exp_data2$PriceRange = "Low Price"
} else if (exp_data2$Price > 10000 & exp_data2$Price <=30000) {
  exp_data2$PriceRange = "Affordable"
} else {
  exp_data2$PriceRange="High"
}

exp_data2$MileRange <- NA
if (exp_data2$Mileage  <= 20000) {
  exp_data2$MileRange = "0-20000 miles"
} else if (exp_data2$Mileage > 20000 & exp_data2$Mileage <=100000) {
  exp_data2$MileRange = "20000-100000 miles"
} else {
  exp_data2$MileRange="+100000 miles"
}

Now let’s evaluate each of these variables:

Price VS Vehicle’s Category

Let’s compare each vehicule’s categories and see how they affect the price:

graphp <- exp_data2 %>%
  group_by(VehiculeCategory) %>%
  summarise(
    meanPrice=mean(Price, na.rm=T)
  )

graphp %>%
  mutate(VehiculeCategory = fct_reorder(VehiculeCategory, meanPrice)) %>%
  ggplot( aes(x=VehiculeCategory, y=meanPrice, fill = VehiculeCategory)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    labs(y="Mean Price", x= "Vehicle Category", title = "Price and Vehicle Categories relathionship") +
    coord_flip()

According to the graph the most expensive category is the SUV while the Sedan cars are way cheaper than others.

Price VS Gearbox

Now let’s compare how the Gearbox type influences the price:

graph1 <- exp_data2 %>%
  group_by(Gearbox) %>%
  summarise(
    meanPrice=mean(Price, na.rm=T)
  )

graph1 %>%
  mutate(Gearbox = fct_reorder(Gearbox, meanPrice)) %>%
  ggplot( aes(x=Gearbox, y=meanPrice, fill = Gearbox)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    labs(y="Mean Price", x= "Vehicle Category", title = "Price and Gearbox type relathionship") +
    coord_flip()

Not surprisingly the Manual models are less expensive than Automatic ones.

Price VS HP

How does the power of the car influence the price ?

graph3 <- exp_data2 %>%
  group_by(Hp)%>%
  filter( Hp < 1000) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_p = mean(Price, na.rm=T)
  )

ggplot(graph3,aes(x=Hp,y=mean_p)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", size=1, color="red")

According to the graph, the more the Hp the car has, the more the car is expensive.

Conclusion

Used car market is a very complex subject because it involves a lot of different factors to set the price of a car. However thanks to this project we will be able to have a more accurate vision of how the prices fluctuate and what factors are responsible for that.

We saw that scarcity and car’s history can play an important part in the first part of our study case, while showing that the best time to buy a used car is 18 after its production in a second time. Finally, we have seen the influence of different factors like the engine power(Hp), the vehicule category, and the gearbox type.

However, the used car market can also be influenced by more complex factors such as the current economy situation of a country, people’s opinion, or the history of the car. For example, if a car is seen in a famous movie, it can make its value highly increase. This is why the used car market can sometimes be inpredictible. Nevertheless, some cars have always been promised to an incredible increase of their price like the Mclaren F1 or the Lancia Stratos Stradale.
